Okay, I looked at the blurb at:

http://hubblesite.org/newscenter/archive/releases/2002/03/

It doesn't state that galaxies mostly turn
counterclockwise (whatever that would mean,
since direction of rotation depends upon the
location of the observer).  What it says is
that its direction of rotation happens to
coincide with the direction in which the
ends of the outer spiral arms are pointing.

I suppose that intuitively people might assume
that a galaxy would rotate in a direction that
would wrap the arms about the center so that the
arms would 'tighten' inwards.  This would roughly
correspond to the way water spirals down a drain.
As the arms are thought to be density waves, I
don't think that such a restriction would
necessarily apply.
